04541nam a22005055i 9780822379546DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t19941994ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223795467 a10.1515/97808223795462doi  a(DE-B1597)553049  a(OCoLC)913464774  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a9472201 aBrown, J. F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHopes and Shadows :bEastern Europe After Communism /cJ. F. Brown. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1 Introduction: The Legacy and the Revolution -- t2 Regional Politics: No Promised Land -- t3 Country Politics: East Central Europe -- t4 Country Politics: South-Eastern Europe -- t5 The Economy: The Painful Ascent -- t6 Nationalism: The Imprisoning Past -- t7 The Yugoslav Tragedy -- t8 The World Outside: New Company and Old -- t9 The Outlook: Precarious But Not Pre-Doomed -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the exuberance that marked the revolutions of 1989, the countries of Eastern Europe have faced the breathtakingly ambitious task of remaking their societies. Simultaneously they have sought to build liberal democracies based on market economics, while confronting reassertions of claims for national independence long suppressed. Taking up where his previous book Surge to Freedom ended, J. F. Brown's Hopes and Shadows analyzes the results of the first four years of Eastern Europe's separation from communist rule and the prospects for the future.The forces at work in the midst of this revolution are examined from a perspective that is necessarily both historical and contemporary as the complex relationship between the tasks that face these countries and the legacy of their communist and pre-communist past shape the difficult present. As the usefulness of the designation "Eastern Europe" is itself questioned, Brown provides both regional and country-by-country analysis of the political situation. The Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, and Poland are grouped together, as are Romania, Bulgaria, and Albania, to address questions such as the development of liberal democratic culture, the activation of democratic institutions and procedures, and the future of former communist bureaucracies. He considers the former Yugoslavia-now torn violently apart-largely as a separate case. The theoretical, political, social, financial, cultural, and psychological dimensions of the transition from socialism to a market economy are discussed in detail. The final aspect of this revolution, the failure of which most immediately threatens the entire process, is the attempt to build new and stable national statehoods. Brown explores the history and impact of the current reemergence of nationalism and the dangers it represents.A comprehensive and authoritative survey, J. F. Brown's analysis and presentation of the contemporary Eastern European political landscape will be essential reading for scholars and specialists and of great interest to general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822379546zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822379546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822379546/original  a978-3-11-071360-2  Duke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  a